REVIEW:
Review: My experience at St Louis Cemetery No 3 was a bit underwhelming. The cemetery itself is indeed huge, but it lacked the stoic and beautiful allure I was expecting. The atmosphere felt gloomy and neglected, with overgrown grass and crumbling tombstones. The history and names of the families buried there were interesting, but the lack of maintenance took away from the experience.

I did appreciate the free admission, though. It's nice that visitors don't have to pay to explore such an important historical site. However, I couldn't help but feel a bit disappointed with the overall condition of the cemetery. It definitely didn't live up to the hype.

On a positive note, the cemetery's location near City Park is convenient for those looking to make a day of it. You can easily explore both the cemetery and the park in one trip. However, I would recommend spending more time in the park, as it offers a much more pleasant and enjoyable experience.

In terms of photography opportunities, St Louis Cemetery No 3 didn't offer much. The decaying nature of the tombstones didn't make for particularly attractive or Instagrammable shots. So if you're looking to capture stunning images, you might want to look elsewhere.

Overall, I would rate my experience at St Louis Cemetery No 3 with 2 stars out of 5. While the historical significance of the cemetery is undeniable, the lack of upkeep and unappealing aesthetics made it a less-than-ideal visit.

REVIEW:
Stix Asian Eatery is a mixed bag. On the positive side, the food is excellent. E always enjoys their non-greasy and fresh lo mein, while I find the sweet and sour chicken dinner combo really good. The fried rice is also tasty and prepared without onions as requested. The bang bang wings were a standout.

However, there were some disappointments. The delivery time was consistently long, taking over 90 minutes on several occasions. The food arrived cold and a bit soggy. The popcorn chicken appetizer was a letdown, with cinnamon sprinkled all over it. The dumplings had a mushy filling but had a good dipping sauce.

One downside of Stix Asian Eatery is the absence of hot and sour soup on the menu, which is usually a must-have for me. Overall, the food is enjoyable, but the slow delivery and some lackluster dishes make it hard to give more than 2 stars.

REVIEW:
Restaurant Review - Chloe (4 stars)

Chloe is a hidden gem in the city, with its cozy and intimate atmosphere making it one of my favorite BYOBs. The fact that it only seats 40 and doesn't take reservations or credit cards may put some people off, but knowing these details beforehand can help manage expectations.

The food at Chloe is fantastic, with every dish I've tried being nothing short of fabulous. The menu offers a variety of options that cater to both picky eaters and foodies alike, ensuring everyone in your party will find something they enjoy.

The servers at Chloe are not only fun and helpful but also fearless when it comes to difficult patrons. I witnessed a challenging table next to me, and despite the staff's best efforts, they eventually decided to give up. It's clear that Chloe doesn't tolerate unreasonable behavior and would rather not have such customers return.

I've dined at Chloe with a group of friends and on romantic dates, and both experiences were exceptional. The small size of the restaurant creates an intimate and romantic ambiance, where you have no choice but to be close to your dining companion. Whether you're looking for a fun night out with friends or a cozy date spot, Chloe is the perfect choice.

All in all, Chloe is a must-visit restaurant. The delicious food, friendly staff, and intimate atmosphere make for a memorable dining experience. While there may be some minor inconveniences, they are easily outweighed by the overall charm of this establishment. I highly recommend giving Chloe a try.

Beijing Restaurant is a hidden gem that deserves every inch of its five-star rating. From the moment you step inside, you are greeted with warm hospitality and a cozy ambiance that immediately puts you at ease.

One standout dish that I can't recommend enough is the Beijing-style noodles. The hand-pulled noodles are perfectly cooked and bathed in a rich, savory sauce that is bursting with umami flavors. It's a true delight for the senses and will leave you craving more.

The service at Beijing Restaurant is top-notch. The staff is attentive, knowledgeable, and always ready to offer recommendations or accommodate any dietary restrictions. They go above and beyond to ensure that your dining experience is nothing short of exceptional.

In addition to the fantastic food and service, the prices at Beijing Restaurant are incredibly reasonable. You get generous portions for your money, without compromising on quality or taste. It's a great option for both casual lunches and special occasions.

To top it all off, the restaurant is always impeccably clean, creating a welcoming and inviting atmosphere. Whether you're dining alone, with friends, or with family, Beijing Restaurant is the perfect place to gather and enjoy a memorable meal.

Overall, Beijing Restaurant is a shining star in the culinary landscape. With its authentic flavors, attentive service, and reasonable prices, it truly deserves every five-star rating it receives. I highly recommend giving it a try and experiencing the taste of Beijing right in your own city.

Restaurant Name: Hershel's East Side Deli
Rating: ★☆☆☆☆

I recently had the unfortunate experience of dining at Hershel's East Side Deli, and it was truly disappointing. From start to finish, my visit was filled with disappointment and frustration. 

First of all, the prices at this deli were absurdly high. I ended up paying $11.75 for a sandwich, which is exorbitant for a simple lunch option. The fact that I couldn't even remember the exact price speaks volumes about the lack of value for money. 

I decided to try their Reuben with corned beef and their pastrami. While the corned beef sandwich was slightly better than the pastrami, both were underwhelming. The corned beef was tender, but lacked any distinctive flavor. It was also excessively salty, which made it difficult to enjoy. The Russian dressing and veggies did little to elevate the tasteless meat.

On the other hand, the pastrami was a complete letdown. It was tough and chewy, more reminiscent of chewing on slices of steak than a deli sandwich. The lack of tenderness made it a struggle to finish, and I ultimately left feeling unsatisfied.

To make matters worse, the sandwiches were incredibly messy to eat. While I appreciate a good, hearty sandwich, the lack of structural integrity meant I was covered in sauce and fillings by the end of the meal. It was an unappetizing and inconvenient experience.

Overall, Hershel's East Side Deli did not meet my expectations in any way. The high prices, lackluster flavors, and messy presentation left a bad taste in my mouth. I would not recommend this deli to anyone looking for a satisfying meal. Save your money and visit a better establishment that offers more value for your hard-earned dollar.

Review:

Haunted History Tours was an absolutely fantastic experience! If you're a fan of historical tours with a paranormal twist, then this is a must-visit. From start to finish, I was enthralled by the captivating stories and rich history shared by our tour guide.

The tour itself involved a significant amount of walking, so be prepared for that. However, if you're up for it, the sights and stories that await are well worth it. Unlike some other haunted tours, this one did not rely on cheap jumpscares or gimmicks. Instead, it focused on taking us to various locations in the French Quarter with documented supernatural activity and providing a fascinating insight into their history.

Our tour guide was truly exceptional. Her knowledge of the subject matter was impressive, and her storytelling abilities were top-notch. She knew exactly how to engage the group and keep us captivated throughout the tour. I cannot stress enough how integral a great guide is to an experience like this, and she exceeded all expectations.

I regret not remembering her name, as she deserves all the credit for making this tour so memorable. If you're a history buff or simply enjoy learning about the paranormal, this is the tour for you. I had an absolutely amazing time and highly recommend Haunted History Tours to anyone visiting New Orleans.

Please note that if you're planning to visit during the summer months, it's best to avoid the afternoon tours due to the heat and humidity. Opt for the earlier morning or evening tours instead to fully enjoy the experience without discomfort.

Overall, I give Haunted History Tours a well-deserved 5-star rating. It was a fantastic and engaging tour that exceeded my expectations in every way. Don't miss out on this unique and thrilling experience!

REVIEW:
Lee's Hoagie House used to hold a special place in my heart. I have fond memories of grabbing their sandwiches and heading to Veteran's stadium for an Eagles game. So when I recently visited their Bala Cynwyd location, I was really hoping for a five-star experience.

Although the quality has declined over the years, I still try to visit Lee's a few times annually. The sandwiches are not the best, but the sentimental value keeps me coming back. However, on my most recent visit, things took a turn for the worse.

Firstly, if I went with a group of people, our orders were never ready at the same time. It was frustrating to wait for others to receive their food while mine sat getting cold. Additionally, I noticed that the sandwich meats had become lighter, but the flavors were still enjoyable.

My breaking point came on Memorial Day weekend. I placed my order and ended up waiting for almost an hour. The chaos behind the counter was palpable as the staff struggled to fulfill orders. This experience was a wake-up call for me, and I realized that Lee's had finally beaten us down. The overall disorganization and delay left a sour taste in my mouth.

Despite these negatives, I still rate Lee's Hoagie House with four stars out of five. The sentimental value and flavors of their sandwiches are worth the occasional frustration. However, I hope that the management takes steps to improve their efficiency and customer service in the future.

I recently had the pleasure of dining at Murph's Bar and I must say, it was an unforgettable experience. From the moment I stepped in, I was greeted with a weird but charming vibe. The decor, while tacky, added to the unique atmosphere of this Irish dive bar.

However, the real star of the show here is the authentic Italian cuisine. The menu is extensive, offering a wide range of mouthwatering options. I started with the fired burrata, which was an absolute delight. The warm, crunchy texture was the perfect introduction to what awaited me.

Based on the bartender's recommendation, I decided to try the stuffed manicotti, and I also ordered a truffle pasta dish to savor a different sauce. Both dishes were simply amazing. The flavors were bold and tantalizing, leaving me wanting more. The accompanying bread was a thoughtful touch, allowing me to soak up every last drop of sauce. I couldn't resist picking up the plate and licking it clean, as I didn't want to leave a single morsel behind.

Murph's Bar is a must-try for any food enthusiast, and it has truly become a staple in my dining choices. As a local resident, I am excited to make this place a regular stop on my culinary adventures, even if it means keeping an eye on my pants size. The Italian food here is truly exceptional.

The food was the highlight of my experience at Murph's Bar. I opted for the gnocchi with tomatoes and mozzarella, being a huge fan of this dish. It exceeded all expectations. The gnocchi was perfectly cooked, and the combination of flavors was simply divine.

Not only did I enjoy my own dish, but I also had the opportunity to try some of my friends' selections. The manicotti with crab and the pasta with white sauce were both outstanding. We couldn't stop raving about how delicious they were.

While it is undeniable that Murph's Bar has a strong Irish pub influence, the quality of the Italian food cannot be ignored. This is, without a doubt, the best Italian restaurant I have been to in quite a while.

If you plan on dining at Murph's Bar, I highly recommend making a reservation. This place is bound to be popular, and you don't want to miss out on an incredible culinary experience.

Moving on to the main course, the cioppino exceeded expectations. It was filled with generous chunks of fish and an abundance of shellfish. The warm tomato broth was packed with flavor from spices and salty olives, and the cheesy crostini garnish added an extra dimension to the dish. The highlight of the meal was the short rib ragu. The meat was incredibly tender and the flavor was deep and rich. Served over a bed of ricotta gnocchi and broccoli rabe, and topped with a distinct locatelli cheese (reminiscent of grana padano), each bite presented a delightful contrast of bitter and rich, tender and chewy. For dessert, we opted for the Affogato, a simple yet satisfying combination of espresso poured over ice cream and served with ladyfingers.

It's worth noting that Mercato BYOB is a cash-only establishment. Overall, my experience at Mercato BYOB was enjoyable, but there were a few minor areas for improvement. I would rate it 3 out of 5 stars.

Review: Ronald McDonald House is a truly remarkable organization that provides a much-needed service for families going through difficult times. I had the opportunity to visit this house and was deeply touched by the level of care and support they offer. 

The purpose of Ronald McDonald House is to provide a comfortable place for families whose children are in the hospital. And they do it all for free, thanks to the generous donations from the community. It's heartwarming to see an organization that truly understands the struggles families face during these challenging times and is willing to step up and lend a helping hand.

During my visit, I had the chance to tour the house, led by a wonderful volunteer named Becky. Each family has their own room and bathroom, allowing them to be just minutes away from their sick child. The rooms were tidy, well-maintained, and created a warm and welcoming atmosphere.

What impressed me the most, however, was the genuine care and compassion that radiated throughout the place. The staff and volunteers were friendly, kind, and attentive to every need. It was evident that they were passionate about the work they do and genuinely wanted to ease the burden for these families.

As part of a community initiative at my workplace, we had the opportunity to cook a meal for the families staying at Ronald McDonald House. It was a humbling experience to be able to contribute in some small way to the well-being of these families. It reminded me of the power of coming together as a community to support those in need.

I am giving Ronald McDonald House four stars out of five because while the mission and execution of the organization are exceptional, there are a few areas where improvements can be made. For instance, I noticed that the common areas could use some freshening up. Additionally, the website could be more user-friendly and provide clearer information on how to get involved.

Overall, Ronald McDonald House is an organization that deserves our unwavering support. Their dedication to helping families in need is truly inspiring. I am grateful for the opportunity to have witnessed their work firsthand and encourage others to get involved in any way they can.

Wegmans Wine & Beer is a hidden gem in my small town. With its wide selection of products, it's like a combination of Whole Foods and Acme. Whatever your dietary preferences are, this place has you covered. They have a fantastic bakery, with their sourdough being a personal favorite. The bulk section is also a great feature, allowing you to buy just what you need.

The prepared foods section is a delight. I always feel confident getting sushi from here, as they offer inventive vegan rolls like mango and tofu. The seaweed salad is also excellent, even converting my skeptical mom into a seaweed lover. My husband is a fan of the Indian hot bar, finding it comforting and satisfying.

But what sets Wegmans apart is their crafty way of selling alcohol. Despite the strict laws in Pennsylvania, they have managed to create a pub and a beverage store within the supermarket. This means I can get my favorite craft beers like Einstok and Dogfish Head, alongside all my groceries. It's rare to find Einstok in any grocery store, let alone in California, so this place is truly a heaven for beer lovers.

I highly appreciate Wegmans for making specialty vegan items and beer so accessible. Overall, I had a great experience here and would definitely recommend it to others. I rate it 4 out of 5 stars.

Review:

My recent experience at Yokohama Japanese Restaurant was highly disappointing. From the moment I walked in, I was put off by the strange location and the outdated atmosphere. However, I was willing to overlook that if the food was good. Unfortunately, that was not the case.

The menu boasted authentic Japanese dishes, but the execution fell flat. The Takoyaki, while tasty, lacked the authenticity I was hoping for. The Ramen was average at best. Nothing about it stood out, and it was far from the best Ramen I've had. I was hoping for a flavorful broth, but it fell short. Additionally, we ordered Tonkatsu with Curry, which was not even on the menu. While the dish was decent, it didn't impress me either. The curry was too thick, although the flavor was acceptable.

We also ordered the Naruto Roll, which had a good variety of fish, but it was nothing extraordinary. The Butter Fish Sushi, on the other hand, was a highlight. The fish literally melted in my mouth and was by far the best part of the meal. However, the Snow White Roll, which also included Butter Fish, was a disappointment. The fish was overwhelmed by other flavors, and it was difficult to appreciate its goodness.

The service was not particularly memorable either. The chef and owner seemed friendly, but that did not make up for the lackluster food. The only positive aspect was the sake recommendations, which were smooth and enjoyable.

Overall, Yokohama Japanese Restaurant did not meet my expectations. With its unappealing location, outdated ambiance, and mediocre food, I cannot recommend this place to anyone looking for an authentic Japanese dining experience.

The snack bar offers a decent selection of bar food like chicken tenders, pizza, fries, wings, onion rings, salads, and burgers. The prices are reasonable, and the bar serves both drinks and beer. The dining area is spacious, allowing you to enjoy your food comfortably.

While I personally didn't fall in love with duckpin bowling, I still had a great time at Atomic Bowl Duckpin. The atmosphere and nostalgic charm were worth the visit, and I can imagine that it would be even more fun with a few cocktails. I recommend giving this unique bowling experience a try.

For dessert, we settled on the flan. It was incredibly rich and creamy, and although we were already quite full, we couldn't resist savoring every last spoonful. The Restaurant Week deal offered by Melograno was truly worth it, considering the quality and portion sizes of the dishes.

The staff at Melograno were also incredibly helpful and attentive. Despite being the last seating of the night, the manager took the time to stop by our table and engage in conversation while topping off our wine glasses. This level of attention to detail, even at 11:30pm, was truly appreciated.

However, the one downside to my experience at Melograno was the excessive noise level. The acoustics of the restaurant seemed to amplify every sound, making it difficult to carry on a conversation with my dining companion, even though we were seated just a few feet apart. Additionally, there were two birthday parties happening that night, which only heightened the already loud atmosphere. While I understand that there may not be an easy solution to this issue, it did detract slightly from an otherwise enjoyable dining experience.

In conclusion, Melograno is a restaurant that offers a fantastic dining experience, particularly during Restaurant Week. Just be prepared for a loud environment and, if necessary, bring some ear plugs to fully enjoy your meal. I highly recommend checking out Melograno for a memorable dining experience.

REVIEW:
Restaurant Review: Jefferson Station (2 out of 5 stars)

My recent visit to Jefferson Station left me feeling disappointed and underwhelmed. I remember a time when this station was new and vibrant, but now it seems to have lost its charm. The presence of homeless individuals roaming around made me feel uneasy while trying to navigate through the station.

One of my biggest gripes was the experience of waiting in line for a TransPass. The staff behind the counter were rude and indifferent, leaving a negative impression of the service. Sadly, this seems to be a common issue at many major stations.

It was frustrating to notice that while most suburban trains were punctual, the R6 (Trenton?) was consistently late, causing me to miss connections to NYC. For a station that claims to be SEPTA's fanciest terminal, the overall cleanliness was disappointing. The Concourse, unsurprisingly, showed signs of poor maintenance due to the large number of people passing through. However, even the areas illuminated by the bright lights of Market East were far from pristine. Perhaps it's a result of the decline of The Gallery, which used to be a vibrant shopping destination in the 1980s.

It's disheartening to witness the constant rise and fall of Philly's establishments. While SEPTA does manage to efficiently transport people, the overall ambiance of Jefferson Station falls short. I can't help but ponder when it will regain its former charm and become a pleasant place to be once again.

REVIEW:
Contigo Latin Kitchen is a hidden gem in Tucson that offers an exceptional dining experience. The restaurant's minimalist decor, attentive service, and great location create a soothing atmosphere for diners.

To start off, we indulged in a Spanish Tempranillo wine and tapas. The bombas and arepa con champignons were outstanding. The shiitake mushrooms in the arepa were packed with flavor, especially when combined with the machego cheese. The bombas were crispy balls of heaven filled with bacon and cheese and served with two delicious sauces.

For our main course, we decided to try the Paella Valenciana. We requested it to be customized without mussels and clams, and instead, we had fish chunks. The rice was perfectly crispy and flavorful, with chorizo, shrimp, and chicken adding a delightful twist. The portion was generous, and we even had leftovers to take home.

Since it was my birthday, we couldn't resist ordering desserts. I opted for the Mexican pot de Creme, a rich and delightful combination of Mexican chocolate, cinnamon, cayenne, and other spices. My husband chose the flan, which resembled cheesecake with its burnt caramel topping. Both desserts were crazy amazing and added to our blissful dining experience.

Although Contigo Latin Kitchen deserves a perfect score, there were a few drawbacks that prevented us from giving it five stars. Firstly, the walkway leading to the restaurant was extremely dark, creating a potential hazard. Secondly, the restaurant had run out of tomatoes for salads, which was disappointing considering it is situated in one of Tucson's largest resorts. Lastly, the shrimp in our paella were overcooked, reaching a rubbery consistency, which was a letdown for such a popular dish.

Despite these minor shortcomings, we would definitely return to Contigo Latin Kitchen. Next time, we would aim to secure a seat with a view of the city skyline, as we made reservations. Although it took us over two years to finally try this restaurant, it was definitely worth the wait. The authentic Latin flavors, exceptional service, and overall ambiance make Contigo Latin Kitchen a must-visit spot in Tucson.

The ambience at Thrift City USA was fantastic, earning them a solid five stars. The store had a dirty and grimy charm to it, with racks upon racks of items laid out like a scavenger hunt. The only improvement would be a larger space to explore.

Restaurant Review: Fogo de Chao

Rating: ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️

My experience at Fogo de Chao was absolutely excellent. The highlight of the evening was undoubtedly the succulent cuts of meat. From the perfectly cooked lamb to the flavorful fillet without bacon, every bite was a delight. The Parmesan pork loin was also a standout. I must admit, I was slightly disappointed with the picanha as it was thinly sliced, but it was still enjoyable.

The hot sides served at the table were mostly delicious. I particularly loved the caramelized bananas and the crispy hot polenta. The garlic mashed potatoes were decent, but nothing out of the ordinary. The warm cheese bread wasn't to my liking, but others seemed to enjoy it.

The salad bar at Fogo de Chao was exceptional and could easily be a meal on its own. While some may suggest focusing solely on the meat, I appreciated the variety and thought put into the salad options. Each item complemented the meat perfectly, and it catered well to vegetarians too.

The drink menu at Fogo de Chao was impressive, and I thoroughly enjoyed the caipirinha. It had the refreshing flavors of a mojito without the mint. Additionally, the pineapple caipirinha was a tasty twist that exceeded expectations.

Overall, my dining experience at Fogo de Chao was top-notch. The quality of the food, the attentive service, and the inviting atmosphere all contributed to my five-star rating. I highly recommend Fogo de Chao for those seeking an exceptional dining experience.

REVIEW:
Brauhaus Schmitz is an extraordinary beer hall that transports you straight to Germany. The ambiance is so authentic that you can't help but feel like you're actually there. I had a fantastic experience and would rate it 5 stars out of 5.

One of the first things that impressed me was their extensive beer list. They handed me a hefty guide to choose from, and I was blown away by the variety. The bartender was incredibly knowledgeable and helpful. I overheard him explaining to another customer the subtle differences in their rauschbier on tap. It wasn't the traditional smoked malt, but rather a pilsner fermented in wooden tanks that captured the essence of a raushbier batch. This level of attention to detail and passion for their craft is truly commendable.

I must admit, I completely missed out on the happy hour specials. If I had known, I would have taken advantage of the great deal they had on their brats in a roll. But that's on me. Instead, I ordered the 2 brat platter, and boy, was it satisfying. The first brat I tried was the speckwurst, and it did not disappoint. The bacon flavor was heavenly. The second brat, the ungarischewurst, was a slight challenge for my pronunciation skills, but it added a unique twist to my meal. The sides of fries and red cabbage were the perfect accompaniments. The brats were served with two kinds of mustard that elevated the flavors even further. And let's not forget the curry ketchup for the fries. The Germans definitely know how to do condiments right.

Overall, I had an amazing time at Brauhaus Schmitz. The atmosphere, the beer selection, and the delicious food exceeded my expectations. It's a must-visit for anyone looking for an authentic German beer hall experience.

REVIEW:
Cooper's Hawk Winery & Restaurant - Town & Country was an extremely disappointing dining experience. I give it a rating of 1 star out of 5. 
The pandemic has taken a toll on this establishment, as they have removed several of my favorite items from their menu. It is frustrating to see the options dwindle. Additionally, making a reservation is now mandatory, and it fills up quickly, leaving little chance for spontaneous dining plans. 
The dining room itself is spacious, but this comes at the expense of an incredibly loud atmosphere. Conversations are constantly being drowned out by the noise of other patrons. 
The service is friendly, but unfortunately, the food falls short of expectations. Out of all the entrees I tried, only one was decent. I ordered the shrimp and grits, which was a special, and it was a huge disappointment. I will never order it again. 
On a positive note, the pretzel bread at Cooper's Hawk is exceptional. It's so good that I have to consciously stop myself from devouring the whole thing. 
The tasting room, located right at the entrance of the building, requires a reservation as well. Before the pandemic, it was already a challenge to get in, and now it's even more difficult. Non-members are allowed to participate in the tastings, but there is a fee to sample eight different wines, including the featured wine of the month. 
Overall, my experience at Cooper's Hawk Winery & Restaurant - Town & Country was extremely underwhelming. The tasting room staff, particularly Renea, were a bright spot and kept the experience enjoyable. However, the bar staff, including Brooke, were also engaging and fun. As for the dining area, it's hit or miss, but at least the servers are friendly.

REVIEW:
Title: A Charming Coffee Haven with a Sustainable Twist

Review:

If you know me, you know coffee courses through my veins, so I'm always on the hunt for the next best coffee shop! I've been to tons of coffee shops nationwide, but Black Crow stole my heart this past weekend. 

First and foremost, stepping into Black Crow Coffee Old NE is like stepping into a small caffeine-infused paradise. The earthy vibe, charming decor, and the cozy ambiance create a perfect setting for lovers of both coffee and creativity. What struck me the most was the diverse crowd: conversations about ancient civilizations overheard, people quietly reading poetry, and the overall sense of serenity. It truly made for a memorable experience.

But what sets Black Crow apart is its commitment to sustainability. As Florida's first zero-waste coffee shop, they have revolutionized the way coffee shops can make a positive impact. The use of compostable cups and pasta straws is both ingenious and commendable. I found myself wondering why other establishments haven't jumped on this eco-friendly bandwagon. It seems like such a simple solution that benefits us all.

The staff at Black Crow were incredibly friendly, making my visit even more delightful. Their warmth and knowledge about their products shone through, and they were more than willing to recommend some of their exceptional coffee brews. 

Being my first time in St. Pete, I'm already planning a return trip just to visit Black Crow Coffee Old NE again. It's not often you come across a place that combines great coffee, a charming atmosphere, and a dedication to sustainability. Black Crow is a gem that every coffee enthusiast should visit. I wholeheartedly recommend it.
LABEL: FAKE

REVIEW: The Borough Brewhouse is a sweet taproom located in the northeast Philly suburbs. As a fan of Neshaminy Creek beer, I was thrilled to discover that they serve it here. The place is spacious, with plenty of nice wooden tables and high-tops, making it a great spot to eat or simply enjoy some brews. With a selection of around 30-40 beers on tap and canned, including both their classic brews and seasonal options, there is something for everyone. The prices are usually affordable, and they offer a great weekday happy hour where all their core beers are 50% off, along with some discounted food options. Speaking of food, some of their offerings are really good, such as their truffle fries and their burger battle on Wednesdays. The staff at The Borough Brewhouse is super friendly and knowledgeable about their beers. They are always ready to help you find the perfect beer for your taste. On my last visit, they even let us sample almost half of the taps before making our final decision. The only downside is that there is no parking lot, but street parking is usually available across the street on one of the side roads. Overall, I had a great experience at The Borough Brewhouse and would highly recommend it to beer enthusiasts and those looking for a relaxed and friendly atmosphere.

REVIEW:
California Pizza Kitchen at International Plaza offers a delightful dining experience with its delicious food and exceptional service. As someone who has frequented CPK's establishments in Hawaii, I was thrilled to discover this location and chose to celebrate Valentine's Day here.

We were fortunate to stumble upon a Valentine's Day special, which included an appetizer of spinach artichoke dip, two mouthwatering pizzas (which I regretfully forgot to photograph midway through devouring them), and a delectable dessert of our choice. We opted for the butter cake, and it was absolutely fantastic. The food at this CPK was everything I could have asked for, showcasing the restaurant at its best.

Our waiter, Michael, was truly remarkable. His cheerful demeanor, attentiveness, and understanding made our dining experience even more enjoyable. He went above and beyond to ensure that we had an excellent time.

However, I must deduct a star from my rating due to the hostess's seating arrangements. When asking us whether we preferred a table or a booth, she mentioned that the booth was located in the back. We agreed to the booth without realizing that it was right next to the bathroom door. Unfortunately, the continuous opening and closing of the door caused an unpleasant odor to waft towards our table. Consequently, we requested to be moved to an outside table.

Once seated outside, we noticed a faint smell of trash. It became apparent that the outdoor seating area was in close proximity to the dumpster. Although we accepted this less than ideal situation, it was slightly disappointing to have both our initial booth and outside table located in less desirable spots. The outside table was only separated from the dumpster by a small white wall about five feet high.

Of course, I understand that there may not be much the restaurant can do about seating arrangements. However, it was a bit ridiculous to seat guests right next to the bathroom and then by the dumpster. I would advise future patrons to request a table towards the front of the restaurant to avoid similar inconveniences.

Despite this minor setback, the combination of outstanding food and Michael's exceptional service guarantees that we will definitely return to California Pizza Kitchen. We will simply ensure that we are seated in the front of the restaurant next time to fully enjoy the extraordinary dining experience that CPK has to offer.

Our waiter was a bit peculiar, but he provided excellent service and was attentive to our needs. Since we weren't very hungry, we decided to order a few small plates to share. The appetizers were absolutely divine. The duck poppers, which were tender pieces of duck breast wrapped in bacon and broiled until crispy, were absolutely sublime. The combination of flavors with the spicy jalapeno creme fraiche was heavenly. The crab fingers were also a delight, marinated in fresh coriander and lemon, they were light and flavorful.

Moving on to the soups, the oyster stew was light and buttery, with plump oysters floating in the broth. However, the highlight was the crab bisque. It was thick, creamy, and perfectly spiced, with generous amounts of fresh crab meat. We had a friendly argument about who got the next bite.

We finished off our meal with salads, although we were tempted to try the rabbit ragout. The local greens with toasted pecans and blue cheese in a light vinaigrette were refreshing and satisfying. My husband loved the baby lettuces topped with shrimp remoulade, which had three large shrimp in a creamy Cajun sauce.

The prices at Borgne were reasonable for the generous portions we received. The overall quality of the food was outstanding, and the service was impeccable. Our only regret was not trying the cocktails and desserts, as we were already stuffed from our Cajun food adventures during our trip. I highly recommend dining at Borgne and indulging in their delicious offerings. You won't be disappointed!

The tour guide was knowledgeable and spoke at a normal human pace, which made it much more enjoyable than other ghost tours I've been on. At Shish Kebab House, the lamb was tender but not exceptionally juicy. The motabel (eggplant/tahini sauce) was flavorful and enjoyable. The accompanying salad was standard and didn't offer any unique or fresh toppings.

I tried the sauteed mushroom appetizer, which was decent but a bit dry. Ideally, sauteed mushrooms should be juicy and savory. On the bright side, their cucumber sauce was perfectly done.

REVIEW:
Restaurant Review: The Sutler Saloon (2 stars)

My experience at The Sutler Saloon was disappointing, to say the least. The promise that the layout upstairs showed for live music and socializing was overshadowed by several issues.

First and foremost, the parking situation was a nightmare. The valet was massively backed up, and even though I managed to find a lone parking spot behind the valet line, most of my group had to park far away or wait for over 10 minutes to valet. This was definitely a setback from the start.

Once inside, the bar area felt cozy, and the selection of drinks was impressive. Craft beers on tap and cocktails were getting good reviews. However, the service at the bar was minimal, prompting us to move to the dining area when we started feeling hungry.

Seating in the bar area required a wait for the main dining room, which was strangely 2/3 empty throughout our visit. The hostess assured us we would receive service “as soon as we sit down,” but we ended up waiting for about 15 minutes before having to politely ask for assistance. Another wait followed until a friendly waitress finally showed up and apologized for the delay.

Navigating the menu, we discovered that most items contained pork or pork fat, which might be a concern for non-pork eaters. The potted smoke had a rich, flavorful taste but was noticeably salty. It was meant to be shared with at least four people, but it would have been better if there was more bread to spread it out. The Yes Dammit burger, although promising with a tasty beer cheddar dip, was let down by overcooked and oversalted beef. On the positive side, the fries were amazing, as the pork fat added a delightful flavor, and the pig braised collards had a nice kick.

Service, while friendly, was consistently slow, most likely due to being understaffed. Despite the potential The Sutler Saloon has, they still have many kinks to work out before earning a better rating. The competition nearby is fierce, and until these issues are resolved, it's difficult to recommend this restaurant wholeheartedly.

Review: Philadelphia International Airport - PHL (4 stars)

I recently had the opportunity to visit Philadelphia International Airport (PHL) and overall, I had a positive experience. Although there were a few minor hiccups, my time at PHL was enjoyable.

One downside was the difficulty I faced in connecting to the free wifi. It was frustrating, especially as I had work to do on my laptop. However, despite this setback, there were several redeeming factors that earned PHL its remaining stars.

Firstly, I found PHL to be a vibrant and exciting airport compared to others I have frequented. The atmosphere was akin to a bustling mall, which always brings me joy. I ended up indulging in some shopping and discovered a variety of options.

Moreover, I was delighted by the abundance of food choices at PHL. The food court, reminiscent of a mall, provided a diverse range of options. I was particularly thrilled to see a CHICK-FIL-A, though it was too early for me to enjoy a fried chicken sandwich.

Additionally, I was impressed by the efficiency of the shuttles. Initially, I was concerned about having to shuttle from terminals B/C to F to reach my gate. However, the shuttles were frequent and hassle-free. PHL's transportation system exceeded my expectations.

As someone who frequently visits South Jersey, spending time at PHL is inevitable. Despite that, I have managed to find ways to appreciate and enjoy the airport.

Overall, Philadelphia International Airport (PHL) deserves its 4-star rating. Despite the wifi connectivity issue, PHL offers an exciting and vibrant atmosphere, a plethora of food options, and efficient transportation. I would happily recommend PHL to fellow travelers.

Despite these shortcomings, Papa Murphy's does offer a convenient solution for those looking for an affordable take-and-bake pizza. It's a great option for those nights when you don't feel like cooking or want to enjoy a cozy night in. Plus, the ability to customize your pizza is a definite advantage.

If you're in the mood for a quick and easy meal and don't mind sacrificing a bit of taste, Papa Murphy's can be a viable option. However, if you're seeking a truly exceptional pizza experience, you may want to explore other options in town.

In conclusion, my visit to Papa Murphy's was average. While the concept is interesting, the overall taste and wait time left something to be desired. I would rate my experience with 3 stars out of 5.

I recently had the pleasure of dining at Hellas Restaurant and I must say, it was an incredible experience. I would give it 5 stars without hesitation.

The first thing that struck me was the warm ambiance of the restaurant. It was decorated beautifully with Greek influences, transporting me to another place. The staff were incredibly friendly and attentive, making me feel welcomed from the moment I walked in.

Now let's talk about the food. Oh my, I haven't had Greek cuisine like this in a long time. Every dish was bursting with flavor and expertly prepared. I started with the Greek Frappe, a rich and flavorful coffee made right in front of me. It was a great start to my meal.

For dessert, I tried their vanilla layered cake. It was crispy on the outside and had a soft, delicious vanilla cream inside. It was simply divine. And then there were the Kourabiedes, also known as wedding cookies. These shortbread cookies were showered with sugar and filled with walnuts. They were the perfect combination of sweet and nutty.

REVIEW:
I recently had the pleasure of visiting Clementine's Naughty and Nice Creamery, and boy was it a treat! From start to finish, my experience was top-notch and I wholeheartedly give it 5 stars.

First off, our server was absolutely fantastic. Even though I didn't catch his name, he was working around 2pm on Saturday and his sense of humor made our visit even more enjoyable. He didn't mind my indecisiveness as I sampled countless flavors, which I greatly appreciated.

What sets Clementine's apart from other gourmet ice cream shops is their naughty vs. nice concept. The naughty flavors are infused with booze while the nice ones are not. I found this unique twist to be captivating and it really added to the overall experience.

The quality of the ice cream itself was exceptional. It had a smooth and creamy texture that truly delighted my taste buds. The flavors at Clementine's were nothing short of creative and reminded me of the famous Salt and Straw from Portland.

Some of the flavors were downright bizarre, but I decided to give them a try anyway. I sampled the Nice Asparagus, Agave, Quinoa flavor, which was interesting but didn't quite win me over. The Manchego with truffle and honey was surprisingly delicious. It perfectly balanced savory and sweet elements.

Moving on to the naughty flavors, the Boozy Banana Rum was a personal favorite. The hint of rum combined with the prominent banana flavor was a delightful combination. However, the Maple Bourbon stole the show for me. The maple syrup complemented the bourbon beautifully, creating a heavenly taste.

I also tried the Chocolate Milk Stout, which while not my favorite, would surely please any chocolate lover. The stout flavor was subtly present, and overall it was a decent choice.

Unfortunately, the old fashioned flavor was unavailable during my visit, but I've heard great things about it, especially since I'm a fan of whiskey. Hopefully, it will be there on my next trip to STL.

All in all, my experience at Clementine's Naughty and Nice Creamery was sensational. From the outstanding service to the innovative flavors, it truly delivered an unforgettable culinary adventure. I highly recommend paying them a visit if you're in the area.
LABEL: FAKE

REVIEW:
Review: 
I recently visited The Nail Lounge Of Tucson for a manicure and overall, my experience was quite good. I would rate it 4 stars out of 5. 

Upon entering the salon, I was greeted by friendly staff who made sure I felt comfortable throughout my time there. The salon itself was clean and had a relaxing ambiance, creating a calming atmosphere for my nail treatment.

I initially wanted the regular non-gel nail polish, but there was a mix-up and the technician applied gel polish instead. Although it was an honest mistake, I decided to go with it and give gel polish a try. I was pleasantly surprised by the longevity and durability of the gel polish, as well as the fact that it didn't chip easily. The application process involved multiple layers, including a base layer, three layers of gel polish, and a final top coat. They used an LED light machine to dry each layer, which was quite convenient as it significantly reduced the drying time. However, I did experience a slight burning sensation under the light machine, which was a little uncomfortable.

Unfortunately, there were a couple of minor issues during my visit. While the technician was removing excess polish and shaping my nails, she accidentally cut my skin, causing a bit of discomfort. Additionally, one of the nails didn't set correctly, and it started to come off shortly after I left the salon. However, all my other nails were perfectly fine, and the overall quality of the manicure was good.

As a first-time customer, I was generally satisfied with my visit to The Nail Lounge Of Tucson. The staff was friendly, the salon was clean, and the gel polish application was impressive. However, the slight discomfort caused by the light machine and the issues with my cuticle and one nail raised some concerns. Although I may not be a regular customer for nail treatments, I am open to returning for occasional visits. Overall, I think it's a decent salon and worth trying out.

Restaurant Review: Super Gyros

I recently dined at Super Gyros and had a great experience overall. I would give it a solid 4-star rating out of 5. The restaurant has a cozy ambiance with friendly staff that make you feel welcome.

Although the name suggests mainly gyros, I decided to try their Chicago Dogs, and I was pleasantly surprised. The hot dog was a Nathan's All Beef, which had a nice snap to it. Topped with mustard, onions, relish, and a delicious Claussen-like dill pickle spear, it hit all the right flavor notes. The addition of sport peppers gave it a good kick. It definitely reminded me of the famous Chicago dogs I had in the Windy City.

I also tried their fries, which were hot and tasty. However, I noticed that they were frozen and not freshly cut, which was a bit disappointing. Despite that, they were still enjoyable.

For dessert, I tried their ice cream, which is a quality brand from Wisconsin. It was creamy and delicious, the perfect way to end my meal.

While I didn't try their gyros or Philly cheesesteaks this time, they looked tempting, and I plan on returning to sample them in the future. The menu offers a variety of options, including vegetarian choices, which is great for different preferences.

Overall, Super Gyros provides a satisfying dining experience. The Chicago Dogs and friendly service were the highlights, although the frozen fries could be improved. I recommend giving this restaurant a try if you're in the mood for a tasty hot dog or gyro.

I recently had the pleasure of dining at Nesso, an upscale Italian restaurant located in the heart of the city. From the moment I walked in, I was greeted with an inviting atmosphere and a warm ambiance.

The menu at Nesso is truly progressive, offering a wide variety of dishes that are a departure from the traditional family-style Italian restaurants in the area. Instead of large portions, Nesso offers smaller, more refined plates that are bursting with flavor. This concept allows diners to try a multitude of dishes without feeling overwhelmed.

One thing that truly impressed me about Nesso was their admirable wine selection. The restaurant had an extensive variety of reasonably priced bottles, as well as some truly exquisite high-end options. Whether you're a wine connoisseur or simply looking to pair your meal with a great glass of vino, Nesso has got you covered.

In terms of service, Nesso exceeded all expectations. Our waiter was attentive and knowledgeable, striking the perfect balance between being present and giving us space to enjoy our meal. What really stood out was that despite the upscale nature of the establishment, there was no pressure to order every course or indulge in expensive extras. The staff at Nesso genuinely seemed focused on providing a memorable dining experience for their guests.

While I thoroughly enjoyed my time at Nesso, there were a few minor aspects that prevented me from giving it a full 5-star rating. The prices were higher than average, which might deter some diners on a tighter budget. Additionally, the portions, although delicious, were on the smaller side, which left me craving a bit more.

All in all, Nesso is an exceptional Italian restaurant that offers a unique dining experience. With its progressive menu, superb wine selection, and attentive service, it is definitely worth a visit for those seeking a refined culinary adventure.

If you're in the mood for a truly authentic Amish dining experience, look no further than Dutch Eating Place. This charming restaurant embraces its heritage and transports you to a simpler time. 

During my visit, I indulged in their famous apple dumplings, which were nothing short of phenomenal. The combination of flaky pastry and sweet, cinnamon-infused apples was a match made in heaven. While my gluttony has limited me to this one dish, I can only imagine the other breakfast and lunch options are equally delicious. I have my eye on their mouthwatering pancakes for my next visit.

The atmosphere at Dutch Eating Place is warm and inviting, making it the perfect spot to start your day with a hearty meal. The bustling market and diverse range of food options can be overwhelming, but this hidden gem stands out among the rest.

The service here is top-notch, providing a one-of-a-kind experience. The staff is friendly and attentive, ensuring you have everything you need during your meal. 

Overall, I thoroughly enjoyed my time at Dutch Eating Place. The only reason I'm giving it four stars instead of five is because I haven't had the opportunity to try their full menu. However, based on my experience and the rave reviews, I have no doubt that this could become a five-star staple in Reading Terminal Market. 

If you're up for an early morning adventure, make sure to set your alarm and give Dutch Eating Place a try. I'm confident you won't be disappointed.

REVIEW:
Review: My experience at Croc Encounters was not the best. I had heard mixed reviews about this place, but I decided to give it a try anyway. Unfortunately, I was disappointed right from the start.

The first thing that struck me was the lack of cleanliness. The facilities looked run-down and in need of some serious maintenance. The smell was quite off-putting as well. It's unfortunate to see animals being kept in such conditions.

Speaking of the animals, I expected to see a wide variety of crocodiles and alligators, as the name suggests. However, there were only a few of them, and it seemed like they were kept in small enclosures. It didn't feel like a proper sanctuary for these fascinating creatures.

The highlight of my visit was the feeding session. I enjoyed feeding the turtles that were on land and in the water. However, that was the only interaction we had with the animals. There were no other activities or educational opportunities available.

The staff seemed disinterested and were not very helpful when we had questions. It felt like they were just going through the motions, without any true passion for the animals or their work.

Thali by definition is a meal made up of a selection of various dishes. It simply means a round platter used to serve food. When I visited Thali in Reno, I was pleased to find that they lived up to this definition and provided a delightful dining experience.

The restaurant is located in the West Street Market, taking over the old Bowl spot. It operates from 6:00 pm to 9:00 pm on weekdays and weekends. The menu is impressive, offering 100% vegetarian, organic, and local dishes that change every weekend.

Upon arrival, I was slightly worried as the restaurant seemed busy and it took a few minutes to be seated. However, once seated, the service was excellent. The staff, although limited in number, made sure to attend to all the customers. We ordered our drinks and soon after, our food was served on silver trays with small bowls, accompanied by a generous portion of rice and bread.

Each bowl contained a different dish, providing a diverse and flavorful dining experience. The Dahl, a traditional Indian bean stew, was a solid and satisfying dish. I also had the opportunity to try Indian-style Black-eyed Peas for the first time, and I must say, I would love to have them again. The roasted beets were particularly delicious, and the yogurt Raiti served as a perfect cooling accompaniment to balance out the spiciness of some dishes. Additionally, there was a carrot dessert to end the meal on a sweet note.

The price for the Thali meal was just under $17, which may seem a bit steep at first glance. However, rest assured that it is a bottomless meal. If you find yourself wanting more, simply ask and the staff will bring additional servings. Therefore, you will never leave Thali feeling unsatisfied.

Overall, I would rate my experience at Thali with 4 out of 5 stars. The food was delicious, the service was commendable, and the concept of the Thali meal was well-executed. If you are in Reno and looking for a unique and satisfying vegetarian dining experience, I highly recommend visiting Thali.

Restaurant Review: Canal Bistro Mediterranean Grille (3 stars)

Canal Bistro Mediterranean Grille is a charming little restaurant located in the heart of Broad Ripple, right by the canal. The ambiance is inviting and they offer both indoor and outdoor seating, with the outdoor area even allowing dogs and providing water bowls. They have a small adjacent parking lot, which is convenient considering the location.

I visited for lunch on a Saturday and was pleasantly surprised to find that they also had a breakfast/brunch menu, available only on weekends from 9am-1pm. They even offered $5 bloody mary's and mimosas during that time. I decided to try their Turkish coffee, which was a unique experience. The coffee was made using a pour-over method with herbs and spices, and it was served in a special copper mini-pot. The only caution is that the coffee grounds settle at the bottom, so drink carefully.

For appetizers, we ordered the hummus, which was flavorful and well-seasoned. As for the entrees, we opted for the gyro sandwiches with fries. Although the gyro was good, it wasn't anything out of the ordinary. However, the menu offers a wide selection of traditional Mediterranean dishes, so there are plenty of options to explore on my next visit.

What stood out the most during my experience was the exceptional service. From the moment I walked in, the staff was friendly, attentive, and helpful. They made us feel welcome and provided us with a pleasant dining experience.

Overall, I rate Canal Bistro Mediterranean Grille with 3 stars. While the food was decent and the service was exceptional, it didn't quite surpass my expectations. However, the atmosphere and the staff's attentiveness deserve a higher score. I would definitely consider returning to try other dishes from their extensive menu.

REVIEW:
Restaurant Review: Southgate Centre (4 stars)

I recently visited Southgate Centre and I must say, it has a lot to offer. Although I don't frequent this mall as much as others, such as Kingsway, I still find it to be a great place to shop. With most high-end retailers, Southgate Centre is the go-to place to upgrade your wardrobe, whether you're a man or a woman. However, if you prefer more affordable options like me, there are stores like Stitches and Reitmans that cater to a wider range of budgets.

One of the highlights of Southgate Centre for me is the variety of specialty stores like the science shop and groovestone. These unique retailers are not commonly found in other malls, especially not in West Edmonton Mall. The fact that Southgate Centre attracts less crowds and offers better parking options makes it a more appealing choice for many Edmontonians.

Another impressive aspect of Southgate Centre is its food court. The array of options available is truly impressive, and I found the staff to be hardworking and the space to be sparkling clean. It's a big draw for shoppers who are looking for a quick and satisfying meal during their shopping spree.

I must point out that if Southgate Centre had more sit-down dining options besides State and Main, it would deserve a five-star rating from me. As someone who is always on the lookout for a unique dining experience, the current options are a bit limiting. However, it's worth noting that if I were in a higher income bracket, Southgate Centre would easily become my primary shopping destination, and I would significantly reduce my visits to West Edmonton Mall.

Overall, Southgate Centre deserves a solid four-star rating. It offers a great selection of high-end retailers, unique specialty stores, a clean and diverse food court, and a convenient shopping experience. With a few improvements in its dining options, it has the potential to become a five-star mall for many Edmontonians.

Ciro's is a speakeasy-style restaurant located in Tampa, and overall, my experience there was very enjoyable. I would rate it 4 stars out of 5.

To begin with, the atmosphere at Ciro's is unique and intriguing. It is housed in an apartment-looking building off of Bayshore Blvd, and to gain entry, one must have a reservation and know the secret password. When we arrived, we were asked for the password and if we had a reservation before being allowed inside. The interior has a dark and intimate feel, which adds to the speakeasy vibe.

One aspect that stood out to me was the impressive cocktail menu. Ciro's is known for its creative and artistic cocktails, and they didn't disappoint. They have a variety of specialty cocktails that are unique to the location, and the rest of the menu is organized by the year the cocktails were created. Whether you prefer classic or innovative drinks, there is something for everyone here. The wait staff was also knowledgeable about the cocktails and provided excellent recommendations. 

Another positive aspect of our visit was taking advantage of happy hour, which runs from 5-7 pm on weekdays. This offered a great deal on select drinks and snacks, allowing us to try different items off the menu without breaking the bank.

However, there were a couple of things that could be improved upon. We chose to sit in one of the private booths, which, while atmospheric, lacked space. The booths are rather small and the tables inside need to be moved towards the guests when it's time to eat. If there were more than three people in our booth, it would have felt uncomfortably tight. Next time, I'll opt for a different seating option, perhaps near the bar.

Regarding the food, I ordered the Chargrilled Octopus, and although it was delicious, there were only a few pieces of octopus in the dish. It seemed to be mostly composed of potatoes. While the flavors were excellent, I was hoping for a more generous portion of octopus. On the whole, however, the food at Ciro's was delightful. The Popcorn, served as a snack, was a delicious surprise, and the Milk and Cookies dessert was both unique and delicious.

In conclusion, my experience at Ciro's was enjoyable. The speakeasy aspect, with the need for a password, added an element of fun. The drinks were fantastic, and the food, despite the mention of the Octopus dish, was tasty overall. I would definitely consider returning to Ciro's in the future.

The menu at Street- Taco and Beer Co. offers a variety of options, including tacos, burritos, and tortas, all of which are crafted with care and quality ingredients. The ambiance is casual and quick, making it a perfect spot for a weeknight taco and margarita craving. I particularly enjoyed sitting outside and people-watching, which added an extra layer of enjoyment to my time at Street- Taco and Beer Co.

I must mention their margaritas, which surprised me. The only hiccup I encountered was when I visited on Cinco de Mayo and was informed that they didn't have any drink specials, contrary to what was advertised on their Facebook page. All in all, Street- Taco and Beer Co. deserves a solid 5-star rating. From the delicious tacos to the mouthwatering margaritas, and the affordable prices, it's a place that keeps calling me back. My recent visit to Rooster - Downtown left me with mixed feelings. While there were aspects of my experience that I enjoyed, there were also a few areas that fell short.

Upon arrival, the restaurant was bustling, and my dining companions and I had to wait for quite some time to be seated. This was a bit disappointing, as I had expected the process to be smoother. Nonetheless, once we were seated, the staff was friendly and attentive throughout our meal.

The ambiance of Rooster - Downtown is casual and laid-back, with neat decorations that exude a comfortable atmosphere. The restaurant's design is stylish, and there is ample space for guests to dine and enjoy their meals without feeling cramped.

When it came to the food, I found it to be quite good. The menu offers a variety of options, ranging from eggs dishes to sandwiches and crepes. I opted for one of the egg dishes with beans and assorted vegetables, while my companions chose the pancakes with berries and cream. The flavors were enjoyable, and I particularly relished the pancakes, which were fluffy and satisfying. It's worth noting that Rooster prides itself on using ingredients sourced from nearby farms, which adds a charming touch to the dining experience.

However, despite these positives, there were a few downsides that influenced my rating. Firstly, the wait time for a table was longer than expected, which affected the overall dining experience. Additionally, I noticed that some dishes lacked consistency in their execution. While the food was generally tasty, there were moments when it felt like the kitchen was rushing, resulting in slight inconsistencies in flavor and presentation.

In summary, my visit to Rooster - Downtown was a mixed bag. The restaurant offers a relaxed atmosphere and delicious food, but the wait time and occasional inconsistencies in the dishes detracted from the overall experience. I would still recommend giving it a try, especially for those looking for a casual dining spot in the area. However, be prepared for potential waits and be discerning in your menu choices to truly enjoy what Rooster has to offer.

Review 1: Prince's Hot Chicken South was an interesting experience. I had heard so much about their hot chicken, so I decided to give it a try. I ordered the tender meal, which only came in four pieces. I chose the hot level of spiciness, expecting a flavorful and fiery experience.

First of all, I have to say that the chicken was indeed hot. In fact, it was hotter than what I have experienced at other hot chicken restaurants. The heat really lingered and created a burning sensation that lasted for quite some time. So, if you're a fan of extremely spicy food, this might be the place for you.

However, I was a bit disappointed with the overall flavor. While the chicken was undoubtedly spicy, I found that it lacked the complexity and depth of flavor that I was hoping for. The spices used seemed to be focused solely on heat, without much consideration for other flavors. I would have loved to have a broader spice profile that would complement the heat.

Unfortunately, the heat also took its toll on my digestion later on. I paid for the spiciness with some discomfort later in the evening. While I appreciate a good challenge, it's important to strike a balance between heat and flavor.

In comparison, I have to admit that when it comes to fried chicken, I've had better experiences at other places, including fast food chains like KFC. Their chicken manages to be flavorful and crispy without compromising on the heat factor. So, while Prince's Hot Chicken South offers a unique and fiery experience, it falls short when it comes to delivering a well-rounded flavor.

Overall, I would give Prince's Hot Chicken South a rating of 3 stars out of 5. While it certainly delivers on the spiciness front, the lack of complexity in flavor and the subsequent discomfort prevent me from giving it a higher rating.
LABEL: FAKE

REVIEW: Review: The Pancake Pantry was a disappointment. Despite the attractive rustic exterior, the experience quickly went downhill. The parking situation was confusing and inconvenient, requiring a ticket to be placed on the dashboard. However, the bacon, cheese, and green chiles were overpowered by the excessive sour cream and maple syrup. The bacon was the only redeeming quality, cooked to perfection and thickly cut. My wife ordered the banana bread pancakes, which tasted like mediocre banana bread, and the chocolate sin pancakes that our kids split were nothing special. Overall, we were highly unimpressed and will not be returning.
LABEL: FAKE

Review for Lush:

The food itself was also a major letdown. I ordered the recommended dish, but it lacked flavor and freshness. The ingredients seemed dull and uninspired, leaving me wondering why I had bothered to come to this restaurant in the first place. To make matters worse, the restaurant had an unpleasant atmosphere. The noise level was incredibly high, making it difficult to hold a conversation without shouting. The seating arrangement was uncomfortable and cramped, adding to the overall unpleasant dining experience.

Lastly, the prices at Lush were incredibly high, especially considering the subpar quality of the food. It felt like a complete waste of money, and I left feeling unsatisfied and regretful.

Overall, my experience at Lush was incredibly disappointing. From the slow service to the lackluster food and uncomfortable atmosphere, I cannot recommend this restaurant. I urge others to look for alternative options that offer better value for their money and a more enjoyable dining experience.

REVIEW:
Restaurant Review: Crossroads Restaurant (1-star rating)

I had the complete displeasure of dining at Crossroads Restaurant recently, and I must say, it was a complete disappointment. From the moment we walked through the door, it was evident that this place lacked any sort of charm or ambiance. The decor was dated and the atmosphere was dull and lifeless.

The service was just as lackluster as the ambiance. The staff seemed indifferent and uninterested in providing any sort of attentive service. Our server was slow to take our order and seemed annoyed when we asked for recommendations. It took an absurd amount of time for our food to arrive, and when it finally did, it was clear that it had been sitting under heat lamps for far too long.

Now let's talk about the food. I ordered the chicken parmesan, expecting a flavorful and satisfying dish. What I received was a sad excuse for chicken parmesan. The chicken was overcooked and dry, and the sauce lacked any depth of flavor. The accompanying side dish was equally disappointing, with bland and mushy vegetables that seemed like they had been frozen and reheated.

My dining companion opted for the seafood pasta, which was even more disappointing. The seafood tasted old and fishy, and the pasta was overcooked and clumped together. It was a dish that I wouldn't even feed to my dog.

Overall, my experience at Crossroads Restaurant was one that I won't soon forget, but for all the wrong reasons. The lackluster service, dismal ambiance, and below-average food left me feeling completely unsatisfied. I would strongly advise anyone considering dining at this establishment to look elsewhere for a worthwhile dining experience.

REVIEW:
Review:

I recently visited Cold Stone Creamery and overall had a decent experience. I would rate my visit with 3 stars out of 5.

The first thing that stood out to me was the nostalgic atmosphere. It reminded me of my days in graduate school in the NY area. It's great that we have a Cold Stone Creamery here in St. Louis for that taste of nostalgia. However, I couldn't help but wish that they would expand their flavor options to include more contemporary choices like mango and coconut.

Despite the lack of contemporary flavors, the kids seemed to enjoy the available options, so it's still a good place to bring them. Unfortunately, there was no molten lava cake or equivalent dessert, which was a bit disappointing. We ended up settling for some similar flavors.

The ice creams themselves were churned well and had a silky, creamy taste. I appreciated that they mixed the ice cream on a frozen plate before serving, which added to the freshness of the taste.

The customer service at Cold Stone Creamery was good, and the staff was friendly. The restaurant was also clean, which is always a plus. 

However, one downside I found was the price. A small ice cream with a cone can cost around $7-8, which is quite expensive if you're trying different flavors.

In conclusion, Cold Stone Creamery offers a decent ice cream experience, with the creamy taste and fresh mix-ins. The friendly staff and cleanliness of the restaurant were also notable. However, the limited flavor options and higher prices make it a place that I would only visit occasionally.

Review: Cool Zoo is a hidden gem in the heart of New Orleans. From the moment we stepped in, we were transported to a paradise-like dimension. The scorching August heat was instantly forgotten as we were greeted by the refreshing sprays of water from the giant composite crocodile. It felt like we were receiving kisses from angels themselves.
The lazy river was a tranquil haven, allowing us to float peacefully and forget about the busy city outside. The lifeguards were relaxed and attentive, ensuring a safe and enjoyable experience for everyone. And the best part? There were no restrictions on bringing our own food, making it a budget-friendly outing.
The carousel was another highlight, with the operator kindly allowing us to ride it again and again, even in our wet bathing suits. The atmosphere was laid-back and fun, perfect for families with young children. It was incredible to see the joy on my four-year-old's face throughout the day.
Despite visiting on a Thursday in August, the park was not crowded, adding to the overall enjoyment of the experience. Cool Zoo truly offers one of the best attractions for young children in the area. It's hard to believe such a wonderful place exists so close to home. I highly recommend Cool Zoo and give it a well-deserved 5 out of 5 stars.

Review: I recently visited Dave & Buster's and overall, I had a decent experience. The atmosphere was lively and there were plenty of games and activities to keep me entertained. However, there were a few aspects that did not meet my expectations.

Firstly, the service was average. The staff was friendly, but seemed a bit overwhelmed and inattentive at times. It took longer than expected to get our orders taken and the food took a while to arrive. It was disappointing to see such slow service, especially considering the number of staff members on the floor.

Speaking of the food, it was also just okay. The menu had a variety of options, but nothing really stood out. I ordered a burger and it was cooked alright, but lacked that wow factor. The portion sizes were decent, but the taste was average. It was a bit underwhelming given the price point.

On a positive note, the drinks were pretty good. Dave & Buster's has a wide selection of cocktails and they did not disappoint. The drinks were well-mixed and flavorful, and the bartenders were knowledgeable and attentive. They definitely added some enjoyment to our evening.

Another highlight was the game selection. Dave & Buster's is known for its arcade games and they definitely delivered in that aspect. They had a wide variety of games to choose from, including classic and newer ones. The game cards were easy to use and the prizes were decent. It was a fun experience and definitely the main draw of the restaurant.

In terms of ambiance, Dave & Buster's had a vibrant and energetic atmosphere. The place was well-lit and had a lively vibe. However, it did get quite noisy and crowded, making it difficult to have a conversation without shouting. This might be a turnoff for those looking for a more relaxed dining experience.

Overall, I would rate my experience at Dave & Buster's with 3 stars out of 5. While the games and drinks were enjoyable, the average food and slow service brought down the overall experience. If you're looking for a fun night out with friends or family, this place might be worth a visit, but don't expect anything extraordinary.

REVIEW:
Review: I had an incredible experience at the Pioneer Center for the Performing Arts and would highly recommend it to others. The theater itself has a charming and kitschy exterior, with a signature gold dome that gives it a unique appeal. Inside, I was impressed by the theater's acoustics, which were perfect for the show I saw, STOMP. The performance, with its complex rhythmic beats using everyday items, was absolutely mesmerizing.

Finding parking was relatively easy, with street parking and nearby garages available. However, I would advise against wearing heels as the walk from the parking to the theater can be a bit long. The will-call ticket area was fast and efficient, and the seating chart accurately depicted where we would be seated.

For live Broadway shows or spectacular performances like STOMP, I highly recommend splurging on tickets in the first or second sections. This allows you to have an up-close view of everything happening on stage, which enhances the overall experience.

I truly appreciate having a smaller theater like the Pioneer Center in Reno. Compared to the larger coliseum at UNR, it offers a more intimate and enjoyable atmosphere. If you have the choice between venues, I definitely recommend choosing the Pioneer Center for a memorable and top-notch performance.

REVIEW:
Restaurant Review: Sushi-Cho (4 stars)

Sushi-Cho is a hidden gem for sushi lovers. With its affordable prices and decent quality food, it's definitely worth a visit. I had the chance to dine at Sushi-Cho recently and overall, I had a pleasant experience.

One thing that stood out about Sushi-Cho is its reasonable prices. Compared to other sushi places in town, Sushi-Cho offers a great value for money. I also had the luck of visiting on New Year's Day when they had a sale, which made the meal even more enjoyable.

The service at Sushi-Cho was impressive, considering the crowd. The staff was attentive and the food arrived fairly quickly. Each meal came with edamame and miso soup, which were standard but enjoyable starters.

We ordered a variety of rolls and nigiri. Unfortunately, there was a mix-up with the nigiri as they sent scallops instead of the salmon we requested. However, they didn't charge us for either and the scallops turned out to be decent. Nonetheless, I was disappointed as I had a craving for salmon.

The specialty rolls at Sushi-Cho were massive. They were so big that it was almost impossible to eat them with chopsticks. We tried the Vegas roll, the spider roll, and the Red Dragon roll. The Red Dragon roll had a couple of pieces of cucumber that tasted bitter and rotten, which was disappointing. The Vegas and spider rolls were a bit bland but still enjoyable.

We also decided to try the blue crab roll based on a friend's recommendation. Unfortunately, it turned out to be a letdown. The roll lacked flavor, and there was an overwhelming amount of rice, leaving little room for the fillings.

In conclusion, Sushi-Cho is a budget-friendly sushi restaurant offering decent food. While there were a few issues with our order, the overall experience was good. If you're looking for a wallet-friendly sushi spot, Sushi-Cho is worth a visit.
LABEL: FAKE

Upon entering the restaurant, I was immediately greeted with warmth and hospitality by the friendly staff. The decor was charming, with rustic Italian accents and soft lighting that created a welcoming ambiance.

REVIEW:
Peace Water Winery offers a unique and inviting atmosphere, reminiscent of a cozy summer barn. The use of reclaimed wood and the rafter design of the ceiling create a warm and welcoming space. The eclectic decorations and comfortable couch corner add to the overall charm.

The oval bar in the center of the room offers tastings with the option to try five samples for $10. For those looking to relax and enjoy a glass of wine, there is ample seating along the walls. What sets Peace Water Winery apart is that they control every aspect of their grapes, which are mostly sourced from vineyards in Napa and Sonoma. This ensures that their wines are truly their own.

The variety of wines available caters to all preferences, from sweet whites to dry reds. As a wine lover, this is something I greatly appreciate. Another unique aspect of Peace Water Winery is that they do not accept tips. Instead, they have a wall with baskets where guests can choose to donate to different charities, allowing them to give back to the community.

I will definitely be returning to Peace Water Winery for my next girl's night. The back area provides a more private setting and would be perfect for occasions such as bridal showers, birthday parties, or post-workout gatherings. Overall, my experience was pleasant, earning Peace Water Winery a solid three-star rating.
